Democracy without popular solidarity
Something has happened to democracy in the sense that the government is elected by the people, and this is true everywhere in the world.
In some way, people have lost faith in elections.
Voter turnout is declining in many countries; in the case of the European Parliament elections, the voter turnout was so low that the legitimacy of the election results is questionable.
Except for voter turnout, we have gotten used to accepting parties or candidates who received 25% of the votes cast as "winners."
From Holland to Finland and on to Argentina and Japan, majority governments are formed based on minorities.
Even the apparent exceptions do not prove the opposite.
Few American presidents have ever been elected by more than 10% of the eligible voters. In fact, half of the eligible voters in the United States have not even registered to vote; of those who have registered, half do not vote; and of those who do vote, less than half vote for the winning candidate.
Even Tony Blair's "earth-shattering" majority in the UK House of Commons stands on shaky ground: The Labour Party received just over 40% of the votes in the last election in 2002, with a voter turnout of 60%.
Therefore, only 24% of the total electorate supported Blair's party.
In most countries, the situation in elections is quite different from what it was twenty, or even fifty years ago.
What has happened?
One possible answer is that voters distrust the political parties.
The electoral democracy functions in most countries due to the mediation of organizations that put forward candidates who advocate for specific packages of political options, for a "manifesto" or a "party program."
For a number of reasons, this long-established practice no longer works.
Ideological party programs have lost their power; voters no longer accept the packages devised by the parties, they want to pick out and choose for themselves.
Moreover, political parties have become machines composed of tightly organized cadres of insiders.
The paradox here is that the parties have become even more clique-like with the loss of their specific ideological orientation.
It is more important to belong to them than to share their specific beliefs.
Such developments have alienated the parties from the voters.
Because most people no longer want to belong to any particular party, only a minority plays along with the party game.
With this, the public's suspicion of political parties grows not least because it is expensive to play along, just like in professional sports.
If the costs are borne by the taxpayer, it is taken badly.
Yet without financial support from the state, parties would have to obtain money through channels that are often questionable, if not even illegal.
Many of the major political scandals of recent decades began with the financing of parties and their candidates.
Other indicators—such as the clear decline in membership—confirm that parties have become unpopular.
Nevertheless, parties are indispensable for a electoral democracy.
The result is an obvious separation between the visible political actors and the electorate.
Because the parties are active in the parliaments, the effects of this separation concern one of the key institutions of democracy.
People no longer believe that the parliaments represent them and are therefore equipped with the necessary legitimacy to make decisions on their behalf.
At this point, a second, rather independent development comes into play.
People are more impatient than ever before.
As consumers, they have become accustomed to immediate satisfaction.
Yet they must wait as voters before they can feel the results of the election they have cast at the ballot box.
Sometimes they never see the desired results.
Democracy requires time not only for elections, but also for deliberations and careful consideration.
The consumer as a voter will not accept this and therefore turns away.
There are alternatives. However, each has its own problems as a democratic solution.
Direct action through demonstrations has become a regular and often effective event.
For less mobile people, it could be replaced by the possibility of expressing their opinion electronically; this ranges from internet chat pages to electronic messages to political leaders.
Then there are also non-governmental organizations. They often have undemocratic internal structures, but they seem to be still more closely connected to the citizens.
In addition, there is of course the possibility of switching off entirely and leaving politics to the experts, in order to focus on other priorities in life.
The latter entails the greatest risks, as it promotes creeping authoritarianism, which is a sign of our times.
But the other signs of the separation between politics and citizens also lead to a rather uncertain situation, because no one can anymore say how representative the prevailing opinions are.
Some would like to cut through the knot by means of more direct democracy.
But a lasting connection between leaders and followers cannot be established by reducing public discussion to simple voting alternatives.
It would be possible to cite many more reasons for remaining committed to the classical institutions of parliamentary democracy and attempting to reconnect them more closely with the citizenry.
Nevertheless, unpopular parties and declining voter participation could turn out to be a temporary phenomenon.
New parties could emerge and bring more vitality back to elections and representative governments.
Yet this is probably not enough to restore the general legitimacy that elected governments have lost.
Therefore, the first concern of all those who care about the constitution of freedom must be to reimagine democracy and its institutions.
